  <div class="ct">
  
<p>If that water were forced down there and then was used to turn steam turbines and earthquakes occured (and they would have occured, for this particular well) i &nbsp;suspect this diary would have been much different. perhaps even ignored, because geothermal energy is green and therefore automatically good, in liberal and progressive spheres. But it's the exact same thing as wastefluid injection.</p>
<p>It's disengenuous to say "fracking causes earthquakes" when in this case, it did not. Fluid injection did. It does not matter where the fluid came from. I realize some liberals and progressives have to have an agenda in all things though even if it means being wrong about something. "Fracking caused Ohio earthquakes" is a far sexier, and scarier headline than "fluid injection caused Ohio earthquakes, a process known to be possible since the 1960s." &nbsp;The first headline is not correct. The second one is correct.</p>
<p>I've never been a fan of being emotionally dishonest or manipulative to stop a distasteful and damaging process. There are roughly 30,000 of these wells nationwide. 99% aren't a problem. That 1% requires there to be some regulation or law to be required because none really exist. You can't even get a successful lawsuit in most states. That was what I was thinking of in my half-snarky response about the caucus diaries.</p>
<p>I'm more willing to listen to and support people who say "I want to regulate and/or ban the injection of fluids into deep wells for all processes" then people who say "I want to regulate and/or ban the injection of fluids created by fracking into deep wells." The second group knows little of what they are talking about. The first group knows there's little to no regulation at all and that this is a major problem.</p>

