  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:52583">terrypinder</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I think the idea that fracking can cause small earthquakes has never been all that outlandish or surprising.</p>
<p>What is unsupported is the idea that fracking can cause large, damaging earthquakes that otherwise would not occur. That is still true. Fracking does not inject enough energy into the crust to create the stresses for a moderate to large earthquake.</p>
<p>What fracking may do is influence what faults break first and exactly when they break. But still, this is potential energy already in the crust that is going to release eventually. Even in places that don't usually experience regular earthquakes.</p>
<p>For reference, a magnitude 4 earthquake feels like a sonic boom, and you'll usually only notice it if you're quite nearby and sitting fairly still in a quiet place.</p>

