  <div class="ct">
  
<p>You're thinking these are shakes. They're just not. They're very very very small. For example, running vibrating equipment inside, like a printing press, or other large machinery would vibrate the building more.</p>
<p>Here is a lesson I learned early on as an engineering student.</p>
<p>We were asked to calculate the downward force that was added to the rear of a car by adding a spoiler.</p>
<p>We calculated that the additional force was about 50 pounds.</p>
<p>"Is that significant?" the professor asked.</p>
<p>Many of us thought so; 50 lbs is noticeable weight.</p>
<p>"Do you see a difference in how your car handles if you put a 100 lb person in the back seat?" he asked. "What about 150 lbs, or two people?"</p>
<p>"Oh." we all realized.</p>
<p>-----</p>
<p>As it happens, seasonal expansion and contraction is in fact very damaging to buildings and to other structures. In my own experience - and remember, I live in California and have lived through several large earthquakes - those seasonal changes are much more damaging to buildings than small earthquakes.</p>
<p>2.0 or less is known as a microearthquake. There are millions of these a year, many of which are unreported because much of the world is not instrumented finely enough to record them.</p>

