  <a href="/user/uid:9653">Debby</a>, <a href="/user/uid:171121">ericlewis0</a>, <a href="/user/uid:52583">terrypinder</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>and think about what it would really cover for you, compared to the cost, and compared to your likely damage. If it is expensive, and if your home is wood frame construction, it may not be a good deal.</p>
<p>If your home is wood frame, where I'd spend your money first is:</p>
<p>- bolting the walls to the foundation<br />
- adding shear resistance to any large expanses of walls (can be done by adding plywood or by adding metal strapping)<br />
- strengthen/retrofit any unreinforced masonry, especially chimneys<br />
- if you have natural gas, consider an earthquake shutoff valve.<br />
- bolt your tall furnishings and bookshelves to the walls, and check to see that nothing heavy might fall on a bed.<br />
- an earthquake/disaster kit with a supply of water, batteries, etc.</p>
<p>A single story wood frame house is very likely to survive intact in even a large earthquake if it is well constructed.</p>

