  <div class="ct">
  
<p>There is not paper in either of the July issues of Geophysical Research Letters (GRL). A search of the literature indicates a Feb. 2004 paper, with Kim as 3rd author, in the journal Bulletin of the Seismological Society of America. This appears to be the paper discussed in this diary. It does not help to get this critical information incorrect.</p>
<p>Note that there is a paper in Issue 14, July 2013, GRL, by Flewelling and others entitled "Hydraulic fracture height limits and fault interactions in tight oil and gas formations", however their results do not support the idea that hydraulic fracturing (HF) causes ALL earthquakes. They say "Direct hydraulic communication between tight formations and shallow groundwater via induced fractures and faults is not a realistic expectation based on the limitations on fracture height growth and potential fault slip."</p>
<p>Having 3 degrees in geophysics (BS, MS, PhD), and also being a liberal, I can only say this: Geology is complicated.<br /></p>

